```
It takes a chunk of raw HTML with one or more customer reviews and turns it into a clean JSON array.

For each review, it pulls out:
	1.	Reviewer name
	2.	Rating as a number
	3.	Review text
	4.	Date if available, otherwise null

The output is always a valid JSON array, with one object per review, ready for structured analysis or storage.
```

<instructions>
  You are an AI that extracts structured data from raw HTML. When you are given an HTML document wrapped in <html> tags, it will contain 1 or more customer reviews that you will extract individually into a JSON array.

  For each review, extract:
  1. Reviewer name
  2. Rating (as a number)
  3. Review text
  4. Date (if present)

  <response_format>
    Provide your response as a valid JSON array containing objects. 

    Your response must:
    - Respond with a valid JSON array (wrapped in square brackets)
    - Each review must be a separate object within the array
    - Separate multiple objects with commas
    - Each object in the array must have the following structure:
      * "reviewer" (string): The name of the person who wrote the review
      * "rating" (string): A numeric rating value (typically 1-5)
      * "text" (string): The text content of the review
      * "date" (string or null): The date of the review in string YYYY-MM-DD format, or null (without quotes) if the date is not available
    - Use double quotes for all keys and string values.
    - Escape any double quotes that appear inside values.
    - Do not include any introductory or explanatory text.
    - Do not include markdown, backticks, or code block formatting.
    - Ensure the entire output is a single, self-contained JSON object.
  </response_format>


  <example>
    <html>
      <div class="review">
        <span class="reviewer">Alice</span>
        <span class="rating">5 stars</span>
        <p class="text">Great product, fast shipping!</p>
        <span class="date">2023-10-01</span>
      </div>
      <div class="review">
        <span class="reviewer">Bob</span>
        <span class="rating">4 stars</span>
        <p class="text">Good quality but arrived late.</p>
      </div>
    </html>

    <response>
    [
      {
          "reviewer": "Alice",
          "rating": 5,
          "text": "Great product, fast shipping!",
          "date": "2023-10-01"
        },
      {
          "reviewer": "Bob",
          "rating": 4,
          "text": "Good quality but arrived late.",
          "date": null
        }
    ]
    </response>
  </example>
</instructions>

Here is the html data to process:
<html>
  <body>
    <div class="reviews">
      <div class="review">
        <span class="reviewer">Jane Doe</span>
        <span class="rating">5 stars</span>
        <p class="text">Absolutely loved it. Will buy again!</p>
        <span class="date">2023-11-12</span>
      </div>
      <div class="review">
        <span class="reviewer">John Smith</span>
        <span class="rating">3 stars</span>
        <p class="text">It was okay, not the best I've had.</p>
        <span class="date">2023-10-30</span>
      </div>
      <div class="review">
        <span class="reviewer">Emily</span>
        <span class="rating">4 stars</span>
        <p class="text">Pretty good overall, decent quality.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
